Scraping Real-Time Data (Streaming APIs)

rtweet makes it possible to capture (a random sample of) live Tweets using the stream_tweets() function, usually 1% during the time window specified. You can specify keywords, as that may be more interesting.

## Stream keywords in tweets happening right now
keywords <- "climate"

## Stream time in seconds 1 minute = 60 For 2+ minutes, simply
## multiply 60 by the number of minutes you want the streaming API to
## stay 'open' If you want to keep it open for hours: (x * 60 = x
## mins, x * 60 * 60 = x hours) E.g. stream for 2 minutes:
streamtime <- 2 * 60

climate_tweets <- stream_tweets(q = keywords, timeout = streamtime, file_name = "climate_tweets.json")
# filename has to be saved in .json here to convert to dataframe

climate_tweets <- parse_stream("climate_tweets.json")
save_as_csv(climate_tweets, "climate_tweets.csv", prepend_ids = TRUE, na = "",
    fileEncoding = "UTF-8")

Collecting tweets by hashtag

the search_tweets function from rtweets allows to perform this task from the rest API. The rate limit should be 18,000 per minute.

# search for 10,000 tweets (no retweets) with brexit hashtag
brexit_tweets <- search_tweets("#brexit", n = 10000, include_rts = FALSE)

To visualise frequency over-time

ts_plot(brexit_tweets, "0.5 hours") + ggplot2::theme_minimal() + ggplot2::theme(plot.title = ggplot2::element_text(face = "bold")) +
    ggplot2::labs(x = NULL, y = NULL, title = "Frequency of #brexit Twitter statuses from past 4 days",
        subtitle = "Twitter status (tweet) counts aggregated using half-hour intervals",
        caption = "\nSource: Data collected from Twitter's REST API via rtweet")

Introducing: Wordclouds!

The code below installs the required text analysis package (quanteda.textplots) and then transforms the Brexit tweet object into a ‘corpus’ object and then into a ‘dfm’ object - where going to learn all about corpus/dfm objects when we’ll introduce text mining in the coming weeks! In the dfm object step, we can remove words that are not particularly meaningful for our aims (e.g. stopwords etc.). With the function textplot_wordcloud we can then generate a wordcloud. The function also allows to specify formatting options, sich as size, total number of words to be included, color …

if (!("quanteda.textplots" %in% installed.packages())) {
    install.packages("quanteda.textplots")
}
library("quanteda.textplots")

if (!("quanteda" %in% installed.packages())) {
    install.packages("quanteda")
}
library("quanteda")


# step 1: remove emoticons (using regular expression for
# emojis/non-ASCII characters)
brexit_tweets$text <- gsub("[^\001-\177]", "", brexit_tweets$text)

# step 2: further text data cleaning + dfm transformation

brexit_corpus <- corpus(brexit_tweets$text)

tweet_dfm <- tokens(brexit_corpus, remove_punct = TRUE, remove_symbols = T,
    remove_numbers = T, remove_url = T, remove_twitter = T) %>%
    dfm()
